			<p class="main-text">
				But still, the best challenge of all that has taken my coding routine to the next level is #100DaysOfCode. I've seen it mentioned a lot on Twitter and I kind of got interested, but then the Code Newbie podcast talked about it in one of the episodes and I finally committed. This was the best decision I've made in a long time. I think the main reasons this challenge works, or at least, worked for me, were: <br>

				- Being pressured to code every single day, even for just a little bit - NO EXCUSES  <br>
				- The ability to look back at the growing log of the passed days <br>
				- Getting instant gratification after posting about your progress on Twitter, receiving likes and reposts and followers <br>

				All of this made my coding hours fun and something to look forward to, not a chore! Every day I would sit down, code, push my code to GitHub, complete a little log entry in my #100DaysOfCode repo on GutHub, tweet an update to my followers and the #100DaysOfCode community, and it felt GOOD. I managed to get one whole freelance project done while doing the Challenge ("Movement Source"), learned a whole new development stack (MEAN, just without Angular), and accumulated a good tweeter follow crowd (200 people is something I could only dream about when I first created my account 4 months before).
